│ An analysis of the bug reveals that the `coro-split` pass incorrectly updates the          │
│ `LazyCallGraph` after transforming a coroutine that is part of a recursive cycle (an SCC). │
│ The pass uses `CG.replaceNode(N, RampFn)` to substitute the original coroutine function    │
│ with a new "ramp" function. However, `replaceNode` is designed for simple replacements     │
│ that do not alter the function's call structure.                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ In the case of mutually recursive coroutines, the transformation breaks the recursion by   │
│ moving call sites. The use of `replaceNode` fails to inform the `LazyCallGraph` of this    │
│ structural change, leaving the graph in an inconsistent state. When the CGSCC pass manager │
│ later re-evaluates the SCC, it discovers that the SCC has been broken by the pass, which   │
│ is an invalid state, leading to an assertion failure.                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct approach is to use an API that handles structural changes to the call graph.   │
│ The fix involves replacing `CG.replaceNode(N, RampFn)` with `N.replaceFunction(RampFn)`    │
│ followed by `CG.updateNodeAfterFunctionChange(N)`. This sequence ensures that the          │
│ `LazyCallGraph` is properly updated by re-scanning the modified function's body for        │
│ changes in its call sites, thus correctly reflecting the (now broken) recursive cycle and  │
│ preventing the crash.                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```patch                                                                                   │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Coroutines/CoroSplit.cpp                                         │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Coroutines/CoroSplit.cpp                                         │
│ @@ -2112,8 +2112,13 @@                                                                     │
│      }                                                                                     │
│    }                                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ -  // Update the call graph to reflect this.                                               │
│ -  CG.replaceNode(N, RampFn);                                                              │
│ +  // Update the call graph to reflect this. We cannot just use replaceNode, as            │
│ +  // that can't handle the case where the function body has changed such that             │
│ +  // it no longer belongs to the same SCC.                                                │
│ +  N.replaceFunction(RampFn);                                                              │
│ +  // Re-scan the function to update the call graph edges.                                 │
│ +  CG.updateNodeAfterFunctionChange(N);                                                    │
│ +                                                                                          │
│    UR.UpdatedFunctions.insert(RampFn);                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│    // Add the new functions to the call graph.                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
