│ The bug is caused by the `coro-split` pass modifying the body of a function within a CGSCC │
│ (Strongly Connected Component) in a way that breaks the recursive cycle that forms the     │
│ SCC. The `LazyCallGraph` is not properly notified of this change. When the CGSCC pass      │
│ manager later checks the validity of the SCC, it finds that the SCC has been invalidated   │
│ by the pass, which is not allowed, and triggers an assertion.                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to explicitly inform the `LazyCallGraph` that the function's body has changed,  │
│ which may alter its outgoing call edges. The correct way to do this is to call             │
│ `updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForFunctionPass`. This function, part of the CGSCC pass         │
│ infrastructure, handles re-scanning the function and updating the call graph and           │
│ associated analyses correctly.                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ By calling this function immediately after `splitCoroutine` (which is where the function   │
│ body is modified), we ensure the `LazyCallGraph` is in a consistent state before any       │
│ further processing. This prevents the assertion failure.                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now apply this fix.                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ <tool_call>                                                                                │
│ {"name": "edit", "args": {"file": "llvm/lib/Transforms/Coroutines/CoroSplit.cpp", "old": " │
│ updateCallGraphAfterCoroutineSplit(*N, Shape, Clones, C, CG, AM, UR, FAM);", "new": "      │
│ // After splitting, the function's body is different. We need to update the\n    // call   │
│ graph to reflect changes to the call sites inside the function.\n    // We do this by      │
│ marking the function as updated in the CGSCC update\n    // result.\n                      │
│ updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForFunctionPass(CG, C, *N, AM, UR, FAM);\n\n                     │
│ updateCallGraphAfterCoroutineSplit(*N, Shape, Clones, C, CG, AM, UR, FAM);"                │
